>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce De Balladon was born about 1100, in Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales as the daughter of Hamelin DeBalladon. She had at least 1 son with Dyfnwal Caradog."},"et":{"about 1100–":"umbes 1100–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1086–1336":"1086–1336","1086–Male":"1086–Surnud","1126–1177":"1126–1177","1065–1103":"1065–1103","1336":"1336","1126":"1126","1103":"1103","1177":"1177","1100":"1100","about 1126":"umbes 1126","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Of,,Monmouthshire,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1100–":"noin 1100–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1086–1336":"1086–1336","1086–Male":"1086–Kuollut","1126–1177":"1126–1177","1065–1103":"1065–1103","1336":"1336","1126":"1126","1103":"1103","1177":"1177","1100":"1100","about 1126":"noin 1126","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","about 1100":"noin 1100","Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of,,Monmouthshire,England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1100–":"environ 1100–Décéd